      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;WingRider_01 wrote:&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Customer service response is in the eye of the beholder. If you request something and they agree with you then the response is great and perfect, if another time you request something and they turn you down then customer service is the pits and is found lacking.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the years I have been playing eq1, I have had to petition a number of times for issues from lost items, ninja looting, intentional training, accidently destroyed items. Some of the responses went my way some did not, now if I let my emotions dictate my response, on the refused petitions then cs response was lacking, if I look at it logicaly, then they did it within their rules and there was no issue.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Riddle me this - is this senario and response customer service lacking or customer service doing what they are supposed to?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Player gets account &amp;quot;hacked&amp;quot; in the investigation by CS, it shows the player handed out the password to their officers of their guild, they in turn handed the information to a member to bot the player for something, this player gave it to their friend to use, their freind logged in the account and stripped it.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The owner logs in and sees that all their PP and droppable equipment is gone, they petition. The petition is refused because of a direct violation of the security policy. The player starts screaming about customer service lacking, but is it?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Like i mentioned, Customer service response is in the eye of the beholder&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;Of course you don't always get what you want or need.  That is not what this topic is about.  This topic is about the channels available to even start the negotiations.  Petitions go unanswered or are answered very slowly.  Sometimes they do not even address the problem associated with the petition, but are rather canned responses.  Calling customer service is even more of a hassle because the line is often in use (I strongly believe there may only be one line).  There are almost no GMs in game to handle issues that do arise.  Why not have a GM on each server who answers petitions?  How can a job like this cost too much, considering the amount of money dumped into this game each month?  I would say that a reasonable person would be happy to just get an answer, whether it goes their way or not.  So no, I do not agree with your assessment regarding service.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
